Quiz 1: Practice Quiz B

You are not logged in.

If you are a current student, please Log In for full access to the web site.
Note that this link will take you to an external site (https://shimmer.mit.edu) to authenticate, and then you will be redirected back to this page.

Please download the .zip file below, which contains all the files, test cases, etc., you need to complete the practice quiz using your own machine. When unzipped it will create its own directory with the quiz's files. The instructions follow below. You'll be editing quiz.py to add the code requested by the instructions.

Download: q1_practice_b.zip

How to take this practice quiz

Set aside a continuous block of time to attempt these problems. This is a past quiz so it can give you a feeling of what an actual quiz is like. During this quiz's semester, though, the quiz was closed book and closed Internet. As such, for the best practice experience, you should attend the quiz under those conditions.

Just like the labs, first run the tests on your computer before submitting online. Good luck!

Submission

When you have tested your code sufficiently on your own machine, you can submit your modified quiz.py below by clicking on "Choose File", then clicking the Submit button to send the file to the 6.009 server. In the real quiz, the server will queue your code and run the tests to score your quiz.

Each test case (not each Problem) must run in 1 second to receive credit.

 No file selected

Instructions

This quiz assumes you have Python 3.6 (or a later version) installed on your machine.

This quiz is closed-book and closed-Internet -- you are only allowed to access the quiz page on the 6.009 website and the material provided in the .zip file. You are not allowed to access other information on your laptop or on the web. You may not discuss the quiz with other students, even after completion of the quiz, until regrades have been completed and final quiz grades assigned (at the end of next week), because many students will still be working on regrades or conflict offerings of the quiz. In the case of this practice quiz, however, you may discuss with other students as part of your preparation for the actual quiz.

In addition to the quiz.py and test.py files, you may also access the library.pdf file, which includes the chapters 1-4 of the Python Library Reference -- they cover the built-in functions (Chap. 2) and built-in data types (Chap. 4). Note that Python's built-in help function will provide a concise summary of built-in operations on data types (e.g., help(set)) or information about the arguments for the built-in functions (e.g., help(sorted)).

As in the labs, test.py can be used to test your code in quiz.py. Each of the problems has a suite of associated tests. You can run tests for a specific problem like so

python3 test.py problem1

or

pytest test.py -k problem1

This quiz is worth 20 points. Your quiz score will be based primarily on performance of your last code submitted during the quiz, tested against 20 test cases. However, points will also be lost in other circumstances:

  • You must not import any Python modules to use as part of your solutions -- quizzes with import statements (or their equivalent!) will be given grades of 0.

  • Having your code check for a specific input (called "hard coding") and then return a specific result is okay only for the base cases in iteration or recursion. Problem solutions that look for specific test case arguments other than base cases are disallowed and will receive no credit.

  • You do not have to include doctests or detailed comments in your code: we will not deduct any points for lack of comments, but encourage those as general good practice.

Aside from these special point deductions above, your quiz score will be based on the number of unittest tests your last submitted code passes. If you pass all of the tests, you'll receive full base credit. If you pass 15 of the 20 tests, you'll receive 75% of the base credit for the quiz (i.e., 15 points). Note also that to pass some of the tests in the time allotted, your solution may have to be reasonably efficient.

Problem 1. vals_at_depth(tree, depth)

In this problem, we want to find all of the elements in a tree that are at a given depth in the tree. A node in the tree is represented as a list with the first element being the node value, and the rest of the list being the node's children. That is to say, our tree structure is a simple nested list structure.

For example, the following code (tree1) and picture represent the same tree.

tree1 = [13,
          [7],
          [8,
            [99],
            [16,
              [77]],
            [42]]]

And similarly, the tree2 definition corresponds to the following picture. This figure also indicates which nodes are at each depth in the tree, corresponding to the example function call and return values below.

tree2 = [7,
          [3,
            [4],
            [1,
              [7]],
            [2]],
          [8,
            [1]]]

We desire a function vals_at_depth(tree, depth) that returns the list of elements in the tree at a specified depth in the tree (where depth 0 corresponds to the root of the tree). The order of elements in the returned list is not important, but the number of times an element appears in the list must equal the number of times that element appears at the specified depth in the tree.

Examples:

  • vals_at_depth(tree2, 0) returns [7]
  • vals_at_depth(tree2, 1) returns [3, 8] or [8, 3]
  • vals_at_depth(tree2, 2) returns (for example) [4, 1, 2, 1]
  • vals_at_depth(tree2, 3) returns [7]
  • vals_at_depth(tree2, 4) returns []
  • vals_at_depth([], 4) returns []

Problem 2. weave(list1, list2)

We are given two lists, list1 and list2, that we would like to "weave" together to produce a single output list, where elements are pulled one at a time alternately from list1 then list2, in that order, until both list1 and list2 are exhausted. For example, weave(['a', 'a'], ['b', 'b']) would produce the output list ['a', 'b', 'a', 'b']. If one of the lists is exhausted before the other, we can continuously draw from the remaining list to continue to weave the output, until both lists are exhausted. Thus weave([1, 2], [3, 4, 5, 6]) would produce [1, 3, 2, 4, 5, 6].

However, we also do not want any element in the output list and its immediately following element to have the same (duplicate) value; that would produce an invalid weave. Instead, if the candidate element from the input list would cause a duplicate, we discard it and try to use the next element from that list instead, successively, until we find a valid element to use in our weave (or until we've exhausted that list, at which point we can return to drawing elements from the other list). Thus weave([1, 2], [1, 3]) would produce [1, 3, 2].

Write the function weave(list1, list2) that implements the above behavior.

Additional examples:

  • weave(['a', 'b'], ['b', 'c']) returns ['a', 'b', 'c']
  • weave(['a', 'b'], ['a', 'c']) returns ['a', 'c', 'b']
  • weave(['a', 'b', 'd'], ['a', 'c']) returns ['a', 'c', 'b', 'd']
  • weave(['a', 'a', 'a', 'a', 'a'], ['b']) returns ['a', 'b', 'a']

Problem 3. all_blobs(world)

Consider a two-dimensional world, consisting of a grid of squares. Each square is either empty (has the value None) or has a string value (e.g., the string 'R'). We are interested in contiguous groupings of squares that hold the same values; we will refer to each such grouping as a "blob". By contiguous, we mean squares that touch on their sides and contain the same value, or touch on the side of squares that are themselves contiguous with other squares also having that same value.

Our representation of such a world is a dictionary, with keys "nrows" being the number of rows, "ncols" being the number of columns, and "grid" being a list of rows, with each row being a list of the column values. The tuple (row, col) = (0, 0) is the upper left corner of this world. An example world is shown as world1 below, with the corresponding picture.

world1 = {"nrows": 5,
          "ncols": 6,
          "grid": [[None, None, 'G', None, 'R', None],
                   ['R', 'R', 'R', 'R', None, None],
                   [None, None, None, 'R', None, None],
                   ['B', 'B', None, 'G', 'G', 'G'],
                   ['B', 'B', None, None, None, None]]}

Our representation for a "blob" will be a list with the first element being the string value that all the squares in the blob share, and the second element being a set containing the coordinates (as tuples) of all of the squares in the blob. An example of a valid blob in this world is ['R', {(1, 0), (1, 1), (1, 2), (1,3), (2,3)}], corresponding to the blob in the second and third row of world1. Note that (0,4) is not a member of this blob, since that 'R' square on the first row does not share a side with any of the squares of this blob -- the diagonal proximity to the 'R' square at (1,3) does not connect the two squares. Thus that single square at (0,4) forms its own blob, ['R', {(0, 4)}]. Empty squares (with value None) do not form blobs.

Your task is to implement the function all_blobs(world) that takes a world dictionary as input, and returns a list of all of the blobs in the world. The ordering of blobs within the returned list is not important, but the list should include all valid blobs once and only once. If there are no valid blobs in world, the empty list [] should be returned. Note that there may be multiple distinct blobs in the world having the same string value (as in the example above where there are two blobs with value R, two blobs with value G, and one blob with value B), and each of those distinct blobs should be in the return list.

Example:

  • all_blobs(world1) returns (for example) [['G', {(0, 2)}], ['R', {(0, 4)}], ['R', {(1, 2), (1, 0), (1, 3), (2, 3), (1, 1)}], ['B', {(3, 0), (3, 1), (4, 1), (4, 0)}], ['G', {(3, 4), (3, 3), (3, 5)}]]

  • all_blobs({"nrows": 1, "ncols": 1, "grid": [[None]]}) returns []

Note that in order to pass some of the test cases, your code will need to be efficient enough to run to completion within the specified timeout.

Each test case (not each Problem) must run in 1 second to receive credit.
